{"key":"post-19582131","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>19582131</id>\n<content>You might be letting the pressure cooker loose pressure too fast at the end of the cycle.&amp;nbsp; Try reducing it to 10 psi for ten minutes, then to 5 psi for ten minutes, etc., until you finally get to zero.&amp;nbsp; Then, let it sit to cool slowly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Another possibility is boiling too soon with insufficient soak time to soften the grains first.&amp;nbsp; Always rinse and begin the soak with hot tap water.&amp;nbsp; This softens and hydrates them slowly so they don't burst.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>19664066</next>\n<prev>19581302</prev>\n<first>19581302</first>\n<last>19669962</last>\n<when>1392694461</when>\n<utime>02/18/14 05:34 AM</utime>\n</post>"}